<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1911-03-24T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1911-03-24T00:00:00-05:00" n="605" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d605">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/1081.</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of the
                                    Treasury</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Treasury Department</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1911-03-24"><hi rend="italic">March 24,
                                1911</hi></date>.</dateline></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: In reply to yours of March 23, inclosing
                            correspondence between the State Department and the Mexican Embassy
                            relating to an alleged prohibition of the ordinary export of supplies
                            across the Rio Grande River, I beg to confirm the explanation given over
                            the telephone, to wit: That the Treasury Department has not prohibited
                            such exportations, and has only enforced the regular and usual
                            requirement that exports and imports be made through established customs
                            ports.</p>
                        <p>Very respectfully,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Franklin
                            MacVeagh.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>